The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

                                        Archives
                                                                                                                                    The City Diary

        A traffic sergeant, Chandan Mukherjee, chased and caught hold of a thief who was fleeing after snatching a cellphone from a pedestrian near Victoria Memorial on Monday evening. Dibyendu Mitra, 45, an employee of a private firm, was walking down the road while talking on his cellphone when someone from behind snatched the handset. As Mitra raised an alarm, Mukherjee chased the snatcher on his motorcycle and arrested him. The phone was recovered from him.
  Calcutta and south Bengal may experience a chilly spell for the next 48 hours. Met officials said the minimum temperature, that had shot up to 16.4 degrees Celsius on Sunday, dropped by about three degrees on Monday. The director of the weather section at Alipore Met office, G.C. Debnath, said cold North Wind is blowing unhindered from the northern parts of the country, leading to a drop in the minimum temperature. We expect the minimum temperature to hover around 13 degrees in the next 48 hours, said Debnath.
  CESC will carry out urgent repairs on the 6-KV switchboard at the Tollygunge distribution station on Tuesday. Power supply is likely to be affected in Khanpur, Pallysree Colony, Gandhi Colony, Netaji Nagar, Moore Avenue, parts of Regent Park, Chandi Ghosh Road, Jadunath Ukil Road, Putiyari Banerjee Para, KM Naskar Road, Kings Road, Ranikuthi Telephone Exchange, Samajgarh Colony and Manick Bandopadhyay Sarani between 10am and 2pm.
  In another daylight robbery in Salt Lake, thieves broke open the door of two apartments on the third floor of Purbachal housing estate and fled with three laptops and other electronic gadgets, worth over Rs 2 lakh. Subhankar Bhattacharya, the sub-divisional police officer of Salt Lake, said the thieves struck between 11.30am and 1.30pm, when the occupants  four students of a management institute in EN block  had gone outside.
  A 50-year-old man died after being hit by a private bus on route 18A at the crossing of Waterloo Street and Old Court House Street on Monday evening. Witnesses took the man to National Medical College and Hospital, where doctors declared him dead. The bus has been impounded and the driver arrested.
      
